This game feels like a dumbed-down version of Spaceflight Simulator; there are far fewer parts, less things you can do with those parts (toggling individual engines repeatedly), and features in the UI that I really liked in SFS but are missing here (switching ships in the map). I realize that this is called SimpleRockets, but that should unjustify the price. To make the price justifiable, there needs to be much more content. I do hope this review helps but this game is a bit of a disappointment.

Were you one of those kids that read Heinlein's children's novels and dreamed of actually building your own rocket? Then this game is for you. It definitely plays to the physics experimentalist in me. I'm *still* trying to blast off from Smercury and fly into the sun! ;-)            Seriously, this game uses a true-to-life physics engine, and I've been playing for hours. This game is *not* for those who like to play mind-numbing games that is all about the "grind". It's for those of us who like to experiment, to build a rocket and to see how it would get from one place to another in the solar system. Then to make a change and see how that change is reflected in flight and/or orbital characteristics.  In other words, if you're a space-nut, a physics-enthusiast or enjoy games that help you learn about and understand the universe, then this game is for you.  Now to tear myself away from this fricken game and get back to my masters thesis!

This game is amazing and what you can do is incredible. My input would be to have an add-on for free or $0.99. It would include burn countdown, stabilization jets, dual/triple chute for heavy weight, glide wings for landing, and solar sails.  Also, a guide to allow ease for launching from one planet and landing on another as in means of course, fuel consumption, idle speed, and etc. Even a  faster speed after say 2,500 km? It took me 10 minutes to get from Smearth to Smars. I also have tried to land on Smars from Smearth, which was extremely hard to calculate but once I finally got near the surface , <1km, I instantly crashed and the planet is shaped strange. Like Smars was a rectangle? I finally got into Smars orbit and got into atmosphere after 20 attempts and then I got ready for a landing and then instant pod destroyed on a rectangle. But I was just happy to get that close. I also noticed that the chute doesn't work on Smars which is some what accurate but a triple chute with just the pod should allow a safe landing. That being said, I know these functions and implementations would be difficult and take a great deal of time and work but these are what I would like to see.

Great game and fun sandbox play. A few things that keep it from five stars - it really needs a (possibly optional) mission planner of some kind. That is, some way to estimate - if I apply the engines here at this thrust for this amount of time, what will happen? Then it would be good for prompts along the mission to pop up. It's just frustrating to get 200km from completing a moon landing, only to run out of fuel... Second, it really needs a way to assemble the parts in a more stable way - Too often, it ends up with the rockets bouncing around, even if you place the side detatchers in such as way that they intuitively should hold together solidly. Otherwise: have fun!

I've been dreaming of a game like this, ever since I discovered "Orbiter" on PC many years ago and lost countless hours trying to explore the solar system and learn about space physics.  SimpleRockets takes this incredibly rewarding and addictive concept, and simplifies it enough to be manageable on a phone, while still being realistic enough to satisfy someone like me.  I would recommend it to anyone looking for a richer more rewarding game that challenges you mind, creativity, and at the same time teaches you a lot, without even realizing that you are being taught something.  People looking for yet another a brainless farmville clone need not apply!

Good game so far, lots of promise. Can't wait to see more diversification with parts (station parts, satellite parts, solar parts, etc.) and moons and such.  My only real quibbles:  1) Change the name of the detacher to decoupler. There's no such thing as a detacher, it's a decoupler and you know it.  2) I'd like the option for zoom buttons in the UI. Pinch-zoom often messes with that big trajectory wheel.  3) I don't care for pretending gas planets have a surface, but not pretending you can't orbit them. I'd prefer to see them true gas planets, but if you're going to fake it make them orbit-able. 4) So far atmospheres are far too easy to escape. Take-offs should be far more difficult.
For the love of GOD, PLEASE make the fastforward/warp/normal buttons larger!

A few things detract from this fun game. I'm not shown any stats on the parts that I'm adding, so I can only guess at the differences between engines by appearance. I don't know how they differ in thrust, fuel consumption, etc, and they're not always logically ordered from least to most powerful. Part descriptions and a ship stat summary would help. Rather than offering a range of parts, the technology you get makes you unable to blast off from some planets. These are obvious no-nos in the simulation genre.
This game hits the spot in so many ways for me. I don't know how realistic the game is, but it's so much fun to learn and the sheer amount of challenge is endless.  All for only a buck!
